# User Documentation Rules

## Purpose

This file defines the standards for user-facing documentation — the documentation that end users, integrators, and operators consult to understand and use the system. This is distinct from architecture documentation (system design) and implementation documentation (build instructions for AI/developers). User documentation is the public face of the system.

> **AI Instruction**: When generating or updating user documentation, follow these rules strictly. User documentation must be accurate, complete, and written for the audience that will use the system — not for the developers who built it.

## Documentation Structure

### Rule DOC-001: Diataxis Documentation Model

All user documentation follows the [Diataxis](https://diataxis.fr/) framework, which divides documentation into four distinct types. Each type serves a different purpose and must not be mixed.

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  DOCUMENTATION TYPES                     │
├──────────────────────────┬──────────────────────────────┤
│                          │                              │
│  TUTORIALS               │  HOW-TO GUIDES              │
│  Learning-oriented       │  Task-oriented               │
│  "Follow me to learn"    │  "How do I...?"              │
│  Step-by-step lessons    │  Recipes for specific goals  │
│  For beginners           │  For practitioners           │
│                          │                              │
├──────────────────────────┼──────────────────────────────┤
│                          │                              │
│  EXPLANATION             │  REFERENCE                   │
│  Understanding-oriented  │  Information-oriented        │
│  "Why does this...?"     │  "What is the exact...?"     │
│  Concepts and context    │  Precise technical details   │
│  For the curious         │  For working developers      │
│                          │                              │
└──────────────────────────┴──────────────────────────────┘
```

**Mandatory sections** for every documented system:

| Section | Diataxis Type | Required | Content |
|---------|---------------|----------|---------|
| Getting Started | Tutorial | Always | Installation + first working interaction |
| Tutorials | Tutorial | Always | At least one per primary user workflow |
| How-to Guides | How-to | Always | At least one per common task |
| Reference | Reference | Always | Complete technical specification |
| Concepts | Explanation | Always | Key domain concepts for users |
| FAQ | How-to | Always | Common questions and troubleshooting |
| Changelog | Reference | Always | User-visible changes per version |

**Do not mix types in a single page**. A tutorial must not include exhaustive reference tables. A reference page must not include step-by-step instructions. Cross-link instead.

### Rule DOC-002: System-Type Documentation Matrix

The documentation scope and emphasis depend on the system's architecture type. Detect the type from the root `ARCHITECTURE.md` and generate accordingly.

| System Type | Primary Reference | Secondary Reference | Tutorial Focus | How-to Focus |
|-------------|-------------------|---------------------|----------------|--------------|
| **REST API** | Endpoint catalog (per resource) | Authentication, error codes, rate limits | First API call, common workflows | Pagination, filtering, webhooks, SDKs |
| **CLI** | Command reference (per command/group) | Configuration, environment variables | First command, pipeline examples | Scripting, automation, CI/CD integration |
| **Web Application** | Feature catalog (per feature area) | Keyboard shortcuts, settings | Account setup, primary workflow | Admin tasks, data export, integrations |
| **Library/SDK** | API reference (per module/class) | Type definitions, exceptions | Import and first usage | Advanced patterns, extension, migration |
| **Agent/Pipeline** | Capability reference (per agent/step) | Configuration, input/output specs | First pipeline run | Custom steps, monitoring, debugging |
| **Hybrid** | Combine applicable types above | Combine applicable types above | Primary interaction mode first | Cross-mode guides |

> **AI Instruction**: When a system has multiple interfaces (e.g., API + CLI + Web), generate reference sections for each. Tutorials and how-to guides should cover the primary interaction mode first, then secondary modes.

### Rule DOC-003: Documentation Source of Truth Chain

User documentation derives from architecture and code. It is never the source of truth — it reflects them.

```
Architecture (source of truth)
    │
    ├── Defines: capabilities, domains, APIs, data models
    │
    ▼
Code (implementation of architecture)
    │
    ├── Defines: exact behavior, public interfaces, CLI commands, config options
    │
    ▼
User Documentation (reflection of architecture + code)
    │
    ├── Translates: technical specs into user-understandable guides
    └── Must match: actual system behavior, not aspirational design
```

**Rules**:
- Never document features that are not implemented
- Never document behavior that contradicts the architecture
- When architecture and code disagree, flag the inconsistency — do not guess
- When the system evolves, user documentation must be updated in the same cycle

## Writing Standards

### Rule DOC-004: Writing Style

User documentation uses a consistent, professional writing style optimized for clarity.

**Voice and tone**:
- Use **second person** ("you") when addressing the reader
- Use **present tense** for describing system behavior ("The API returns a JSON object")
- Use **imperative mood** for instructions ("Run the following command", not "You should run")
- Be **direct** — avoid hedging ("This will create a user", not "This should create a user")
- Be **concise** — one idea per sentence, one topic per paragraph

**Terminology**:
- Define every domain-specific term on first use
- Maintain a glossary page for terms used across multiple pages
- Use the same term consistently — never alternate between synonyms
- Match the terminology used in the system itself (CLI flags, API field names, UI labels)

**Formatting**:
- Use code formatting for: commands, file paths, field names, values, environment variables
- Use bold for: UI elements, important warnings, key concepts on first mention
- Use admonitions (note, warning, tip, danger) for: caveats, prerequisites, shortcuts, breaking changes
- Use tables for: parameter lists, option comparisons, status codes

```markdown
<!-- CORRECT: Clear, direct, well-formatted -->
## Create a user

To create a new user, send a POST request to `/api/v1/users`:

```bash
curl -X POST https://api.example.com/v1/users \
  -H "Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN" \
  -d '{"email": "user@example.com", "name": "Jane Doe"}'
```

The API returns a `201 Created` response with the user object.

!!! note
    Email addresses must be unique. If the email already exists,
    the API returns `409 Conflict`.

<!-- INCORRECT: Vague, passive, poorly formatted -->
## Users

Users can be created by sending requests. You should probably use
POST and put the data in the body. The email should be unique or
it might not work.
```

### Rule DOC-005: Code Examples

Every feature, endpoint, command, or configuration option must include at least one working example.

**Example requirements**:
- Examples must use **realistic data** (not "foo", "bar", "test123")
- Examples must be **copy-pasteable** — the reader should be able to run them directly
- Examples must show both the **input and expected output**
- Examples must specify the **language** in fenced code blocks
- For API endpoints: show `curl` and at least one SDK/language example
- For CLI commands: show the command and its output
- For configuration: show a complete, minimal configuration block

```markdown
<!-- CORRECT: Realistic, complete, shows output -->
```bash
$ myapp users create --email "jane@acme.com" --name "Jane Doe"
Created user:
  ID:    usr_7f3a2b1c
  Email: jane@acme.com
  Name:  Jane Doe
```

<!-- INCORRECT: Unrealistic, no output -->
```
myapp users create --email foo@bar.com --name test
```
```

**Multi-language examples** (for APIs and libraries):

Use tabs or clearly labeled sections to show examples in multiple languages. At minimum, include the system's primary language and `curl` for HTTP APIs.

## Organization

### Rule DOC-006: File Naming and Directory Structure

All user documentation lives under `docs/user/` following a strict directory structure:

```
docs/
├── user/
│   ├── index.md                    # Landing page: what this system does, who it's for
│   ├── getting-started/
│   │   ├── installation.md         # How to install/set up
│   │   └── quick-start.md          # First working interaction
│   ├── tutorials/
│   │   └── {workflow-name}.md      # One per primary user workflow
│   ├── how-to/
│   │   └── {task-name}.md          # One per common task
│   ├── reference/
│   │   ├── api/                    # If system has API
│   │   │   └── {resource}.md       # One per resource/endpoint group
│   │   ├── cli/                    # If system has CLI
│   │   │   └── {command-group}.md  # One per command group
│   │   └── configuration.md        # All configuration options
│   ├── concepts/
│   │   └── {concept-name}.md       # Key domain concepts
│   ├── faq.md                      # Frequently asked questions
│   ├── glossary.md                 # Term definitions
│   └── changelog.md                # User-facing version history
└── mkdocs.yml                      # Portal configuration
```

**File naming rules**:
- Use **kebab-case** for all file and directory names
- Use **descriptive names** that match the page title (e.g., `create-api-keys.md`, not `api-keys-create.md`)
- Prefix tutorial files with a number for ordering if needed (e.g., `01-first-pipeline.md`)
- Keep file names under 50 characters

### Rule DOC-007: Documentation Versioning

Documentation follows the system's semantic versioning:

- **Major version**: new documentation version (may restructure, remove pages)
- **Minor version**: new pages, new sections, expanded content
- **Patch version**: corrections, clarifications, typo fixes

**Version tracking**:
- The documentation landing page (`index.md`) displays the current version
- The changelog (`changelog.md`) records all user-visible changes
- MkDocs Material's version provider can serve multiple versions simultaneously

**Version tagging**: when deploying documentation, tag it with the system version to enable version switching in the portal.

### Rule DOC-008: Cross-Referencing

Every documentation page must link to related pages. Isolated pages are a navigation dead end.

**Required links**:
- Tutorials link to the relevant reference page ("For all options, see [Command Reference](../reference/cli/commands.md)")
- Reference pages link to relevant tutorials or how-to guides ("For a step-by-step example, see [Tutorial: First Pipeline](../tutorials/first-pipeline.md)")
- Concept pages link to both tutorials and reference ("To see this in practice, see... For the full API, see...")
- How-to guides link to reference for complete option lists

**Link format**: use relative Markdown links that resolve within MkDocs. Never use absolute URLs to your own documentation.

**"See also" sections**: every page ends with a "See Also" or "Related" section listing 2-5 related pages.

## Changelog and Release Notes

### Rule DOC-009: User-Facing Changelog

The user-facing changelog (`docs/user/changelog.md`) differs from the architecture changelog. It describes changes **from the user's perspective**, not the developer's.

**Format**:
```markdown
# Changelog

All notable changes to {System Name} are documented here.
This changelog follows [Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/) format.

## [Unreleased]

### Added
- New `export` command for downloading reports in CSV format

### Changed
- The `--format` flag now defaults to `json` instead of `text`

### Deprecated
- The `--legacy-auth` flag will be removed in v3.0. Use `--token` instead.

### Removed
- Removed support for configuration file format v1 (deprecated in v2.0)

### Fixed
- Fixed pagination returning duplicate results when filtering by date
```

**Writing rules for changelog entries**:
- Write from the user's perspective ("New `export` command", not "Added ExportService class")
- Include the affected command, endpoint, or feature name
- Mention migration steps for breaking changes
- Link to relevant documentation pages for new features

## Portal Configuration

### Rule DOC-010: MkDocs Material Standards

The documentation portal uses MkDocs with the Material theme. The configuration must include:

**Required plugins**:
- `search` — full-text search across all documentation
- `minify` — HTML minification for production

**Required features**:
- Navigation tabs (top-level sections as tabs)
- Navigation sections (expandable sidebar groups)
- Navigation path (breadcrumbs)
- Table of contents integration (right sidebar)
- Code copy button
- Content tabs (for multi-language examples)
- Admonitions (note, warning, tip, danger blocks)

**Required extensions**:
- `pymdownx.highlight` — syntax highlighting
- `pymdownx.superfences` — fenced code blocks with Mermaid support
- `pymdownx.tabbed` — content tabs
- `admonition` — admonition blocks
- `toc` with permalink — table of contents with anchor links
- `attr_list` — attribute lists for images and elements

**Configuration location**: `docs/mkdocs.yml` (at the docs root, not inside `docs/user/`)

## Quality Assurance

### Rule DOC-011: Documentation Review Checklist

Before marking user documentation as complete, verify all items:

```markdown
## Documentation Completeness Checklist

### Structure
- [ ] Landing page (index.md) exists with system overview
- [ ] Getting Started section with installation and quick-start
- [ ] At least one tutorial per primary user workflow
- [ ] At least one how-to guide per common task
- [ ] Complete reference for all public interfaces
- [ ] Concepts section explaining key domain terms
- [ ] FAQ with at least 5 common questions
- [ ] Glossary with all domain-specific terms
- [ ] Changelog initialized

### Content Quality
- [ ] Every page has a clear title and introduction
- [ ] Every feature/endpoint/command has at least one example
- [ ] Examples use realistic data (not "foo", "bar")
- [ ] Examples show both input and output
- [ ] No jargon used without definition
- [ ] Second person ("you") used consistently
- [ ] Imperative mood for all instructions

### Navigation
- [ ] MkDocs configuration resolves all pages
- [ ] Every page has a "See Also" section with 2-5 related links
- [ ] All internal links resolve (no broken links)
- [ ] Breadcrumbs and sidebar navigation work

### Accuracy
- [ ] Every documented feature exists in the implementation
- [ ] No undocumented features exist in the public interface
- [ ] All code examples are runnable
- [ ] Configuration options match actual defaults
- [ ] Error messages match actual system output

### Traceability
- [ ] Every tutorial traces to a vision capability or user workflow
- [ ] Every reference page traces to an architecture component/API
- [ ] Every concept page traces to a domain concept in the architecture
```

## Documentation Evolution

### Rule DOC-012: Documentation Update Triggers

User documentation must be updated when any of the following occur:

| Trigger | Documentation Action |
|---------|---------------------|
| New feature implemented | Add reference page + tutorial or how-to guide |
| Feature behavior changed | Update all affected pages (reference, tutorials, how-to) |
| Feature removed | Remove pages, add migration guide if needed, update changelog |
| API contract changed | Update reference, examples, and any affected tutorials |
| CLI command changed | Update command reference and affected how-to guides |
| Configuration option added/changed | Update configuration reference |
| Error behavior changed | Update FAQ and troubleshooting |
| New domain concept introduced | Add explanation page, update glossary |
| System version released | Update changelog, version tag, landing page version |

**During system evolution** (Prompt 08):
1. Identify which user documentation pages are affected by the architecture/code change
2. Update affected pages to reflect new behavior
3. Add new pages if new features or concepts are introduced
4. Remove or redirect pages for removed features
5. Update the user-facing changelog
6. Verify MkDocs navigation still resolves

**Documentation must never lag behind the implementation by more than one version**. If the system is at v2.1, documentation must cover at least v2.0.

## Audience Awareness

### Rule DOC-013: Know Your Reader

Documentation is written for the system's **users**, not its developers. The audience depends on the system type:

| System Type | Primary Audience | Technical Level | Assumes Knowledge Of |
|-------------|-----------------|-----------------|----------------------|
| REST API | Backend developers | High | HTTP, JSON, authentication |
| CLI | DevOps engineers, developers | Medium-High | Terminal, shell basics |
| Web Application | End users, admins | Low-Medium | Web browsers, basic computing |
| Library/SDK | Developers in target language | High | Language ecosystem, package management |
| Agent/Pipeline | Technical operators | Medium-High | Configuration files, data formats |

**Adjust accordingly**:
- For **low-tech audiences**: avoid technical terms, use screenshots, explain every step
- For **developer audiences**: be precise, show code, assume familiarity with tools
- For **mixed audiences**: provide a quick path for experts and a detailed path for beginners

### Rule DOC-014: Accessibility

User documentation must be accessible:

- Use descriptive alt text for all images and diagrams
- Ensure sufficient contrast in custom styling (rely on MkDocs Material defaults)
- Use semantic heading hierarchy (h1 > h2 > h3, never skip levels)
- Provide text alternatives for video content
- Keep paragraphs short (3-5 sentences maximum)
- Use lists for sequential steps or parallel items

